8) The ifconfig command (or ip addr in modern systems) displays details about network interfaces such as:

IP Address – The address assigned to the device.

MAC Address – Hardware address of the network interface.

MTU (Maximum Transmission Unit) – Maximum packet size that can be transmitted (commonly 1500 bytes for Ethernet).

RX/TX Packets – Number of packets received and transmitted.

Status – Indicates whether the interface is UP or DOWN.

The iwconfig command is used for wireless interfaces and provides:

SSID (Network Name)

Frequency

Signal Strength

Bit Rate (Speed)

Mode (Managed/Monitor)

These commands help analyze network configuration, performance, and connectivity status.

9)Accessing the Home Router Web Interface

To access the router settings, first open the Command Prompt and type:

ipconfig

From the output, identify the Default Gateway address under the active network adapter.

In this case, the Default Gateway is:

192.168.43.1

Next, open a web browser such as Chrome, Edge, or Firefox and type the Default Gateway IP address in the address bar:

http://192.168.43.1

Press Enter.

The router login page will appear. Enter the administrator username and password to access the router dashboard.

Inside the router interface, the Connected Devices section displays:

Device names

IP addresses

MAC addresses

Connection type (wired or wireless)

Thus, the router web interface allows monitoring and managing all devices connected to the network.





10)DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) automatically assigns IP addresses to devices in a network.

The process follows four steps (DORA process):

Discover – The device broadcasts a request for an IP address.

Offer – The DHCP server offers an available IP address.

Request – The device requests the offered IP address.

Acknowledge – The server confirms and assigns the IP.

The DHCP server also provides:

Subnet mask

Default gateway

DNS server address

Lease duration

This automation avoids manual configuration and prevents IP conflicts.

